132nd MAINE LEGISLATURE
FIRST REGULAR SESSION-2025
Legislative Document No. 1085
H.P. 707 House of Representatives, March 18, 2025
Resolve, Directing the Judicial Branch to Perform an Inspection and
Study of the Rumford Courthouse Building
Received by the Clerk of the House on March 14, 2025. Referred to the Committee on
Judiciary pursuant to Joint Rule 308.2 and ordered printed pursuant to Joint Rule 401.
ROBERT B. HUNT
Clerk
Presented by Representative HENDERSON of Rumford.
Cosponsored by Senator CARNEY of Cumberland and
Representatives: CARUSO of Caratunk, LEE of Auburn, O'HALLORAN of Brewer, SATO of
Gorham, Senator: MARTIN of Oxford.
Printed on recycled paper

1 Sec. 1. Judicial branch to perform inspection and study of Rumford
2 Courthouse building. Resolved: That the judicial branch shall perform an inspection
3 and space study of the building that houses the Rumford Court located at 145 Congress
4 Street, Rumford, including the space occupied by the Rumford Police Department, to
5 determine the feasibility of necessary updates required to resume jury trials at the building,
6 including all required updates, structural and cosmetic improvements and an estimated
7 timeline for completion of the renovations.
8 Sec. 2. Report. Resolved: That, by April 1, 2027, the judicial branch shall issue a
9 report on the inspection and space study, including all required updates, structural and
10 cosmetic improvements and an estimated timeline for completion of the renovations. The
11 judicial branch shall issue the report to the joint standing committee of the Legislature
12 having jurisdiction over judicial matters, which may report out a bill based upon the report.
13 SUMMARY
1144 This resolve directs the judicial branch to perform an inspection and space study of the
1155 building that houses the Rumford Court and issue a report within 18 months of the effective
1166 date of this resolve on all the necessary updates, structural and cosmetic improvements
1177 required and an estimated timeline of completion of renovations to resume jury trials in the
1188 building.
